<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>This  jupyter-notebook contains some examples on how to visualize scientic data in a chemistry context using the python libraries <a href="https://pandas.pydata.org/">pandas</a> and <a href="https://seaborn.pydata.org/">seaborn</a>.</p>
<p>Pandas is a library that comes quite handy with tabular data (aka dataframes), and provides function to manipulate this data:</p>
<p><code>pip install pandas</code></p>
<p>Seaborn is a nice plotting library that can work with the Pandas dataframes:</p>
<p><code>pip install seaborn</code></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

</pre></div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>This dataset is a nice collection of about 30,000 melting points for different chemicals and is available from <a href="https://figshare.com/articles/Jean_Claude_Bradley_Open_Melting_Point_Datset/1031637">here</a>. It also contains some additional information like name of the compound or the identifier from the <a href="http://www.chemspider.com/">Chemspider</a> database (csid).</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
